Concerning the three main points that you describe as weaknesses, I must say  that: 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs36 \
i) The treatment of missing values. I have a general agreement with almost all that you mention. My treatment of missing values is simplistic, and it is biased. I would have loved to the selection function (which I presume is a combination of the probability of detection and the probability of selection). However, we currently do not have it. As it is now stated in the manuscript, and I think you will agree with me, it would require numerical simulations (either Monte Carlo or the galaxy model in that region). Either that or a hierarchical model in itself. I think in the previous versions I have failed to transmit the practical impossibility of either approach, and also the fact that it lays somehow beyond my current objectives. My main objective was to create the BHM for it to be applied not just in that specific data set but in future ones. Characterising the data sets in such a deep way is something that we have discussed within our group. The ones working in statistics always ask the ones in the data reduction to provide at least some lower or upper limits, with no luck so far. This is something that I hope to do in my postdoc. Currently the best I can do is try to put some rough approximations to the regions of completeness in the marginals of the observable space. These are the ones I call completeness limits for the magnitude distributions and for the spatial distribution. Of course the correlation between them make my marginal limits very simplistic. Extracting a region of completeness from such patchy observable space will be a nightmare, particularly if we want to maximise the number of known cluster members and minimise the size of the data set. As I explain some lines ahead, I tried to do it, just in the photometric subspace and it resulted in a larger sample than that selected using the membership probability. The membership probability is a good approach because, given the low probability of leave one cluster member out of the restricted sample, we can assume that the rough completeness limits of the larger sample apply to the cluster sample. Thus, the probability of selection (which is different from the probability of detection) can be assumed to be one. This is an assumption that is later validated, we found no new cluster member in the larger sample. \
\
My treatment is simplistic, but nevertheless renders less biased results that if the incompleteness were ignored. I fully recognise that in the general case the use of a uniform prior for the distribution of missing values (i.e. assuming missing at random) is of little help. However, as I prove to you with a very simple example, and as\cf4  \cf0 it is now proven in the manuscript, this very simple assumption, in the particular case of the data set I have, renders far better results than working just with the subsample of completely observed objects. Something that has been done by the previous works. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs36 \
ii) About the objectivity in the prior, I do agree that in the abstract I stated it in a very simplistic way. Of course there is no way to fully avoid the subjectivity of the prior, but the hierarchical approach offers the least subjective way to do it. However, even in the case of a fully hierarchical model (mine is just partially hierarchical), the subjectivity would not vanish. If you allow me to say it in this way, no decision is guarantied to be fully objective. Even in the frequentist approach, where there are no priors (well there are but not explicitly stated) we can always put in question if the chosen likelihood is completely objective.
\f1\fs24 \
