\f0\fs36 \cf0 In the hierarchical model, as you correctly pointed out, the subjectivity moves to the next level. By moving the subjectivity upwards, the lower levels become less subjective. In the plain model the subjectivity lies in the choice of prior. In the hierarchical model I do not use one prior for the model parameters but an infinite collection of priors parametrised by the hyper priors, and it is the data themselves that constrain the posterior distribution over the priors. I firmly believe that the hierarchical model is far less subjective than the plain model would have been. So the question is not whether I have completely eradicated subjectivity, but whether or not I have decreased it.  
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs36 \
About using the data twice for settling the priors, yes I am doing it with a subtle consideration. For the hyper-priors values, it is true that I use some of the data that I later use in the likelihood, but notice that in fact my prior information, the one used for the hyper-priors, is given by the previous estimates of membership probabilities from the literature (the ones done by Bouy et al. 2015) so formally speaking, it is not exactly the same data. This is equivalent to a three level hierarchical model in which the second level parameters, the ones that I am fixing with the data and a priori membership probabilities, are also inferred from the data. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs36 \
iii) The debatable choice of the i-Ks colour index. I hope you agree with me that the a priori information (I am not referring to a prior probability) should be used whenever available. In particular, if others have already proven its usefulness. As it is stated in the manuscript, Sarro et al. 2014 did a detailed analysis on the discriminative power of all the observables (except the sky positions) that are in the data set that I am using. They showed that the particular combination of observables that I use is the best one to discriminate between cluster and field objects as measured by the mean decrease in accuracy, and by the mean node impurity obtained from out-of-bag (OOB) samples and a random forest classifier.\cf4  
\f1\fs24 \cf0 \

\f0\fs36 \
As it is now stated in chapter three, the i-K colour index is a good empirical estimator of the effective temperature, which in turn, as proven by our current understanding of stellar models, is, together with the mass and metallicity, the main element driving the spectral energy distribution of stars.\cf4  \cf0 A different colour index based only on infrared colours would be insensitive to temperatures in most of the stellar mass range.
